certifications:

to view certificates which connected to apiserver: 
/etc/kubernets/manifests/kube-apiserver.yaml

openssl 509 -in /etc/kubenerts/pki/apiserver.crt -text -noout # viewing your cert

viewing logs:

issues with certs in kubernets:
journalctl -u etcd.service -l 

installing by kubeadm
kubectl logs etcd-master

crictl ps -a
crictl logs containerID 

--tls-cert-file=/etc/kubernetes/pki/apiserver.crt # file used for kubeapiserver certificate
--etcd-certfile=/etc/kubernetes/pki/apiserver-etcd-client.crt # Identify the Certificate file used to authenticate kube-apiserver as a client to ETCD Server.
--kubelet-client-key=/etc/kubernetes/pki/apiserver-kubelet-client.key # Identify the key used to authenticate kubeapi-server to the kubelet server.
--etcd-cafile=/etc/kubernetes/pki/etcd/ca.crt # Identify the ETCD Server CA Root Certificate used to serve ETCD Server.

What is the Common Name (CN) configured on the Kube API Server Certificate?
openssl x509 -in /etc/kubernetes/pki/apiserver.crt -text -noout


Use this command to generate the base64 encoded format as following: -
cat akshay.csr | base64 -w 0

Finally, save the below YAML in a file and create a CSR name akshay as follows: -
---
apiVersion: certificates.k8s.io/v1
kind: CertificateSigningRequest
metadata:
  name: akshay
spec:
  groups:
  - system:authenticated
  request: <Paste the base64 encoded value of the CSR file>
  signerName: kubernetes.io/kube-apiserver-client
  usages:
  - client auth

  What is the Condition of the newly created Certificate Signing Request object?
  kubectl get csr
  kubectl certificate approve akshay
kubectl apply -f akshay-csr.yaml
